To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. This function allows you to end the program's execution immediately. Here's an example of how to use it:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your code here

    // Terminate the program
    exit(0);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, `exit(0)` is called at the end of the `main()` function, which will terminate the program with a status code of 0, indicating successful execution. You can also use `exit(1)` or any other integer value to indicate an error or specific status.

Remember to include the `<stdlib.h>` header file at the beginning of your program to use the `exit()` function.

